      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Section 52 Disclosure When Selling Property in Queensland
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        What a Section 52 disclosure statement is, what it must include, and what happens if it is wrong. Getting this right before you sign a contract is not optional.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Under the Property Occupations Act 2014, Queensland sellers of residential property must provide a disclosure statement to the buyer before a contract is entered into. This document is commonly called the Section 52 disclosure, named after the section of the Act that requires it. It is not a formality. Errors or omissions in a Section 52 disclosure can give a buyer the right to terminate the contract, sometimes right up to settlement, at no cost to them. For sellers, understanding what the disclosure must cover and getting it right before signing is one of the most important steps in the sale process.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a Section 52 disclosure must cover</h2>
      <p>The disclosure statement must include accurate information across six main areas. First, all encumbrances registered on the title at the time of sale. This includes mortgages, easements, covenants, caveats, and any other interests registered on the Certificate of Title. Buyers need to know what comes with the land and what does not disappear at settlement. A mortgage, for instance, will be discharged at settlement, but an easement for drainage or access is a permanent feature of the land that transfers to the buyer.</p>

      <p>Second, any statutory notices affecting the property. This covers notices issued by local councils, utility providers, or government bodies that the seller is aware of, including proposed resumption notices, infrastructure charges notices, or outstanding show cause orders. If a council has issued a notice about a retaining wall or illegal structure, it must be disclosed.</p>

      <p>Third, body corporate information for properties within a community titles scheme. For units, townhouses, and some freestanding homes within a scheme, the disclosure must include current levies, any special levies approved or proposed, details of significant current or pending litigation, and recent meeting minutes. Body corporate information is particularly important because unexpected levies or ongoing disputes can materially affect a buyer's decision to proceed.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Pool safety, smoke alarms, and sustainability</h2>
      <p>The disclosure also requires sellers to address pool safety compliance. If the property has a pool, the seller must either provide a current pool safety certificate issued by a licensed pool safety inspector, or provide the buyer with a Form 36 notice indicating that no certificate will be provided and allowing the buyer to arrange their own inspection. Sellers who choose the Form 36 path cannot insist the buyer accepts the pool in its current condition. The buyer retains rights under the compliance framework.</p>

      <p>Smoke alarm compliance must also be declared. Queensland's 2022 requirements mandate interconnected photoelectric smoke alarms in every bedroom, on every storey, and in hallways connecting sleeping areas to the rest of the house. Sellers must declare in the disclosure statement whether the property currently complies. Properties that do not comply must be brought into compliance before settlement unless the buyer agrees in writing to accept a price adjustment in lieu of compliance. In practice, most buyers want the work done, not a token credit.</p>

      <p>A sustainability declaration is required for residential properties. It covers insulation in the ceiling, hot water system type, and energy features such as solar panels. The sustainability declaration does not create compliance obligations, but it must be honest. Declaring that ceiling insulation exists when it has been removed or was never installed creates grounds for a claim.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Disclosure versus warranty</h2>
      <p>A distinction that matters for sellers: the Section 52 disclosure is not a warranty that the property is in good condition. It is a disclosure of known legal and administrative facts about the title and the property's compliance status. The building and pest report is separate. Defects in the structure, termite activity, or general condition are not Section 52 matters unless they have resulted in a formal notice from a regulatory authority.</p>

      <p>Sellers sometimes assume that disclosing an issue in the Section 52 protects them from all liability. This is not accurate. Disclosing an encumbrance or a notice does not mean the buyer must accept it. In some cases, it gives the buyer information they need to negotiate or to walk away. What the disclosure does is satisfy the statutory obligation to inform. What happens next is a matter of negotiation and contract terms.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens if the disclosure is wrong</h2>
      <p>If a Section 52 disclosure is materially incorrect or incomplete, the buyer may have the right to terminate the contract at any time before settlement. This termination right applies even if the buyer has already gone unconditional on their finance and building inspections. The seller does not automatically have an opportunity to correct the error and hold the buyer in. This is the risk that makes accuracy at the disclosure stage so important.</p>

      <p>The most common causes of disclosure errors in practice are: failing to list all registered encumbrances, providing outdated body corporate levy information, declaring smoke alarm compliance when the property has not yet been upgraded, and issuing the disclosure before the pool safety certificate has been obtained. Each of these is avoidable with proper preparation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to prepare the disclosure correctly</h2>
      <p>The disclosure statement is typically prepared by the seller's solicitor or conveyancer, drawing on a search of the title register, body corporate records where applicable, and information provided by the seller about notices and compliance status. Sellers should not attempt to complete the disclosure themselves without legal assistance. The searches required are specialist work, and the consequences of errors are significant.</p>

      <p>Before your solicitor prepares the disclosure, gather what you know: any notices you have received about the property, your most recent body corporate correspondence including levy notices, the pool safety certificate if you have one, and any documentation about the smoke alarm upgrade. The more complete the information you provide, the less likely the disclosure will contain an error that causes problems later in the campaign.</p>

      <p>Agents need the disclosure statement before or at the time contracts are being presented. If a buyer signs a contract before receiving the disclosure, there are complications around the buyer's cooling-off rights that create additional risk for the seller. The clean sequence is: disclosure prepared, disclosure provided to buyer, then contract signed.</p>

